have elected to have settled, or presumed to have been spawned, upon his island.  Then, as if he were not desirous of resting his claim on its mere legal merits, he would remind them of the superiority of his grain, and the impossibility of a scarcity, in
 
the event of which calamity an insular people could always find a plentiful though temporary resource in sea-weed.  He then clearly proved to them that, if ever they had the imprudence to change any of their old laws, they would necessarily never have mor
e
 than one meal a day as long as they lived.  Finally, he recalled to their recollection that he had made the island what it was, that he was their mainstay, and that his counsel and exertions had rendered them the wonder of the world.  Thus, between force
, and fear, and flattery, the Vraibleusians paid for their corn nearly its weight in gold; but what did that signify to a nation with so many pink shells!
