\par {\pntext\pard\plain\b\f1\fs20\cf6\cgrid0 \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 14.\hich\f1 \'b6\loch\f1 27\tab}}\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx900{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls17\pnrnot0\pndec\pnb1\pni0\pncf6\pnf1\pnfs20\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnsp120 {\pntxtb 14.\'b6}}
\faauto\ls17\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1\cgrid0 But while, notwithstanding an universal toleration, such an unanimity of taste apparently prevails throughout the island, as if Fruit were a subject of such peculiar nicety that d
ifference of opinion must necessarily rise among men, great Fruit factions even now prevail in Vraibleusia; and, what is more extraordinary, prevail even among the admirers of pine-apples themselves.  Of these, the most important is a sect which professes
 
to discover a natural deficiency not only in all other fruits, but even in the finest pine-apples.  Fruit, they maintain, should never be eaten in the state in which Nature yields it to man; and they consequently are indefatigable in prevailing upon the l
e
ss discriminating part of mankind to heighten the flavour of their pine-apples with ginger, or even with pepper.  Although they profess to adopt these stimulants from the great admiration which they entertain for a high flavour, there are, nevertheless, s
ome less ardent people who suspect that they rather have recourse to them from the weakness of their digestion.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx900\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1\cgrid0 
