ic instructor jumped up in the person of Mr. Flummery Flam, the least insinuating and the least plausible personage that ever performed the easy task of gulling a nation.  His manners were vulgar, his voice was sharp, and his language almost unintelligibl
e
.  Flummery Flam was a provisional optimist.  He maintained that everything would be for the best, if the nation would only follow his advice.  He told the Vraibleusians that the present universal and overwhelming distress was all and entirely and merely 
t
o be ascribed to 'a slight over-trading,' and that all that was required to set everything right again was 'a little time.'  He showed that this over-trading and every other injudicious act that had ever been committed were entirely to be ascribed to the 
